player.seasonOutlook: Atwell was selected by the Rams in the second round of April's draft. The Louisville product is one of the tiniest players in this year's rookie class at 5-foot-9, 155 pounds. He's a terrific athlete with outstanding game speed, explosiveness, elusiveness and big-play ability, but he isn't going to handle traffic or contested situations very well. Atwell is primarily a slot target (92% over the past three seasons) and figures to be used as a situational screen/gadget and vertical home-run target in the pros. He may have trouble finding his way to consistent snaps and targets in 2021 with Robert Woods, Cooper Kupp, Van Jefferson and DeSean Jackson also in the fold. The second-round investment and Sean McVay's productive offense makes him worthy of a late-round flier.

The Packers drafted Rodgers in the third round of April's draft. The Clemson product is a 5-foot-9, 210-pound receiver/rusher/punt returner. Built like a back, Rodgers is not coincidentally very good after the catch and is a quality tackle breaker. He has good speed, strength and hands, but his lack of length hurts his separation ability and could limit him to slot duties (or perhaps even a conversion to RB) in the pros. Rodgers' 6.4 aDOT over the past three seasons is second-lowest in this class and he handled only 15% of the targets and 11% of the air yards in Clemson's offense. He'll look to carve out a slot/punt returner role, but he'll have his hands full finding a consistent offensive role with Randall Cobb, Allen Lazard, Marquez Valdes-Scantling and Devin Funchess in the mix. He's barely worth late-round consideration.

Mims is entering his second NFL season after appearing in nine games as a rookie. The 2020 second-round pick was heavily used out of the gate with seven-plus targets in four of his first five NFL games but was reduced to a total of 11 targets during his final four outings. Mims was utilized as a vertical threat (15.3 aDOT) but caught only 50% of his 46 targets and didn't find the end zone. Mims has a great combination of size (6-foot-3), speed (4.38 40-yard dash) and quickness (6.66 three cone), but has plenty of competition for work with Corey Davis, Elijah Moore and Keelan Cole added to a WR room that also includes Jamison Crowder. Mims' skill set and talent make him worth a late-round flier, even in a rebuilding Jets' offense.

Miller flirted with flex value during the first half of the 2020 season, but his stock plummeted in a hurry once Antonio Brown returned from suspension in Week 9. Of course, even before Brown came back and with Chris Godwin missing four of the first eight games, Miller sat 40th at WR in fantasy points with a 25-400-2 receiving line. He was limited to an 8-101-1 line as a situational player the rest of the regular season. For the season, his 15.1 aDOT was fifth highest among WRs. Brown, Mike Evans and Chris Godwin are all back for 2021 and youngsters Tyler Johnson and Jaelon Darden are also competing for work off the bench. The 24-year-old Miller doesn't need to be drafted.

Jordan was selected by Houston in the fifth round of April's draft. The Miami product stands 6-foot-3, 247 pounds and has the tools to eventually emerge into an NFL starter. He has good speed, separation, and tackle breaking ability, which shows him in his class-leading 8.2 RAC over the past three seasons. He's a bit undersized, which raises concerns about his catch radius and abilities in contested situations, but if an NFL team finds ways to get the ball in his hands - as Miami did with screens and flat routes - Jordan can eventually emerge into an offensive threat. Of course, he's well down the depth chart in Houston for the time being and should only be drafted in deep dynasty leagues.
